/xwords/entry.php?entryID=1076 Kumano Shinkō], accessed on October 6, 2008</ref><ref>[http://www.sekaiisan-wakayama.jp/english/s_sanzan.htm Kumano Sanzan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609225919/http://www.sekaiisan-wakayama.jp/english/s_sanzan.htm|date=2008-06-09}}, World Heritage Registration Association, accessed on October 13, 2008</ref> The kami enshrined in the three Kumano Sanzan Grand Shrines and worshipped in [[Kumano shrine]]s are the three Kumano mountains: Hongū, Shingū, and Nachi.<ref name="kumano" /> * {{ill|Nezu Gongen|ja|根津神社#歴史|lt=Nezu Gongen|12=draft}} ([[根津神社#歴史|根津権現]]) * {{ill|Ochi Daigongen|ja|越知大権現|1=Ochi Daigongen|12=draft}} ([[越知大権現]]) – Hakusan Shugendō ([[白山修験]]) * {{Interlanguage link|12=draft|Omatsu Daigongen|ja|お松大権現}} * {{ill|Sanki Daigongen|ja|三鬼大権現|12=draft}} ([[三鬼大権現]]) * {{nihongo|{{ill|Sannō Gongen|ja|山王権現|12=draft}}|山王権現}} or {{nihongo|Hie (alternatively ''Hiyoshi'') Sannō Daigongen|日吉山王大権現}} is a guardian deity worshiped in [[Tendai]] spread from [[Mount Hiei]]. It is treated as a Buddhist title of Shinto [[Oyamakui no Kami]]. * {{Interlanguage link|12=draft|Sekison Gongen|ja|石尊権現}} * {{ill|Seiryū Gongen|ja|清瀧権現|12=draft}} ([[清瀧権現]]) was enshrined in [[Jingo-ji]] in Takao as the tutelary kami of [[Shingon Buddhism]] by [[Kūkai]].<ref>Jaanus, ''Seiryū Gongen'', accessed on October 6, 2008</ref> * {{ill|Shiramine Daigongen|ja|白峯大権現|12=draft}} ([[白峯大権現]]) * {{ill|Suzuka Gongen|ja|片山神社 (亀山市)|lt=Suzuka Gongen|12=draft}} ([[片山神社 (亀山市)|鈴鹿権現]]) – {{ill|Shamanism|ja|巫覡|12=draft}} ([[巫覡]]) * {{ill|Tateyama Gongen|ja|立山権現|12=draft}} ([[立山権現]]) – Tateyama Shugendō ([[立山修験]]) *{{ill|Yuga Daigongen|ja|瑜伽大権現|12=draft}} ([[瑜伽大権現]]) * {{nihongo|{{ill|Zaō Gongen|ja|蔵王権現|12=draft}}|蔵王権現}} or {{nihongo|Kongō Zaō Bosatsu|金剛蔵王菩薩}} is a deity worshiped in [[Shugendō]].<ref>Encyclopedia of Shinto, [http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=201 Zaō Gongen], accessed on October 6, 2008</ref>
